@suuuehgi if you want, can you submit a change to main.rs which fixes this bug on your system without the need to prepend the env var?

Currently the code looks like this:

```
fn main() {
    #[cfg(target_os = "linux")]
    {
        if std::path::Path::new("/dev/dri").exists()
            && std::env::var("WAYLAND_DISPLAY").is_err()
            && std::env::var("XDG_SESSION_TYPE").unwrap_or_default() == "x11"
        {
            std::env::set_var("WEBKIT_DISABLE_DMABUF_RENDERER", "1");
        }
    }

    handy_app_lib::run()
}
```

I'm guessing we can make this conditional less specific? We already try to set this on x11

> [@suuuehgi](https://github.com/suuuehgi) if you want, can you submit a change to main.rs which fixes this bug on your system without the need to prepend the env var?
> 
> Currently the code looks like this:
> 
> ```
> fn main() {
>     #[cfg(target_os = "linux")]
>     {
>         if std::path::Path::new("/dev/dri").exists()
>             && std::env::var("WAYLAND_DISPLAY").is_err()
>             && std::env::var("XDG_SESSION_TYPE").unwrap_or_default() == "x11"
>         {
>             std::env::set_var("WEBKIT_DISABLE_DMABUF_RENDERER", "1");
>         }
>     }
> 
>     handy_app_lib::run()
> }
> ```
> 
> I'm guessing we can make this conditional less specific? We already try to set this on x11

Yes, I suspect so. The logic here is: `has GPU with direct rendering support` AND `is not Wayland` AND `identifies as X11`.

`/dev/dri` is present on virtually every modern Linux system and I suspect it doesn't really make sense in this context. If the latter ones are mutually exclusive the code / logic should actually be equivalent to:

```rust
fn main() {
    #[cfg(target_os = "linux")]
    {
        if std::env::var("XDG_SESSION_TYPE").unwrap_or_default() == "x11"
        {
            std::env::set_var("WEBKIT_DISABLE_DMABUF_RENDERER", "1");
        }
    }
    handy_app_lib::run()
}
```

But the bug is not just present on X11, but also on Wayland. Neither is it limited to NVIDIA ([as sometimes hinted](https://github.com/tauri-apps/tauri/issues/9394)) as I'm using the Intel iGPU with Wayland.

For now I would hence just disable the DMABUF renderer completely.

```rust
fn main() {
    #[cfg(target_os = "linux")]
    {
        // DMABUF renderer causes crashes on various GPU/display server configurations
        // See: https://github.com/tauri-apps/tauri/issues/9394
        std::env::set_var("WEBKIT_DISABLE_DMABUF_RENDERER", "1");
    }
    handy_app_lib::run()
}
```

