@cjpais This is a problem with Wayland protocols. Applications are not allowed to register global shortcuts themselves.

Tauri doesn't support global hotkey on Wayland. [tauri-apps/global-hotkey#28](https://github.com/tauri-apps/global-hotkey/issues/28). However, xdg-desktop-portal has `org.freedesktop.portal.GlobalShortcuts` for apps to register global shortcues. This is already used by chromium. It might be easier using crate `ashpd`.  But I am unsure whether this works outside of KDE/GNOME.

To avoid the Wayland hell, another solution is provide CLI options and let users bind hotkeys themselves in their setting center / compositor config.

@tmikaeld I think the permissions required for simulating input can be workaround by packaging with separate privileged binary with rules etc.

Besides virtual keyboard, an alternative might be input method engine (text-input-v3). This means we have to implement an ibus or fcitx5 plugin, which means interoperate with C/C++.

Have to say that both of these are a bit out of scope of a Tauri app lol.

@tmikaeld I tested `Enigo` crate with `wayland` flag and executed it as normal user.

`enigo::platform::Enigo::key` can type in unicode character but cannot trigger compositor hotkey for some reason. But, `enigo::Keyboard::text` is able to type arbitrary unicode text sucessfully, which means we might not be needing to deal with clipboard etc. at all!

UPDATE: it turns out Enigo registers zwp_input_method_v2 (which coordinates with text-input-v3 as I mentioned earlier) under the hood, which means it competes the slot with ibus/fcitx5, which means we'll have to restart ime after enigo does its job.

